Ah, actually, I figured I can easily add it myself and that&#39;s probably why Symfony doesn&#39;t provide anything like that out of the box. Just add the following method to the entity class:

    public function setData($data)
    {
        foreach ($data as $key =&gt; $value)
        {
            $this-&gt;$key = $value;
        }
    }

it&#39;s ugly but, in the foo class:

    function setData(array $data) {
        foreach($data as $key =&gt; $value) {
            $this-&gt;$key = $value;
        }
    }

this obivously circumvents the setter logic, so

    function setData(array $data) {
        foreach($data as $key =&gt; $value) {
            $func = &#39;set&#39;.ucfirst($key);
            $this-&gt;$func($value);
        }
    }

you might even write some global 

    function setDataOnObject(array $data, object $object) {
        foreach($data as $key =&gt; $value) {
            $func = &#39;set&#39;.ucfirst($key);
            $object-&gt;$func($value);
        }
    }

this obviously all requires, that the setters actually exist...

you could also use the [serializer component][1] as enricog suggested in their comment. Or you could use the property access component, which will by itself find the right setters or adders.


  [1]: https://symfony.com/doc/3.4/components/serializer.html#deserializing-in-an-existing-object

