    System.out.println(&quot;Was it a sorted list: &quot; + myStings.equals(sortedList));

The list `equals()` method checks that both lists are of the same size and that all corresponding pairs of elements in the two lists are equal.

Oh, I&#39;ve just added a step above to convert all the elements in your list to lowercase. Only difference it&#39;ll make in the example above is where the word &quot;Mary&quot; sits in your sorted list, but overall shouldn&#39;t make a difference to what you are trying to achieve.  

UPDATE:

So the reason this method does not work specifically for your implementation is because you are not actually using Lists (or anything from `java.util.Collections` for that matter). You&#39;ve created your own implementation of a linked list. Hence when you use the `.equals()` method your actually using the default implementation of this method found in `java.lang.Object`. The default implementation does not check what&#39;s in the Object, but rather it checks if the the Objects share the same **memory address**. Where your`sort()` method is returning a *sorted* list, it&#39;s a different object sitting in a different address in memory, hence `.equals()` will report it as `false`;

What you need to do is actually check the variables in your object (not the memory address). In order to do so you will need to `Override` the default implementation of `.equals()` in your `ConsLoString` class, because you actually want to do comparisons on the variable `first`

So it&#39;ll look something like this... 

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object o) {
      ConsLoString toCompare = (ConsLoString) o;
      if(this.first == toCompare.first) {
        if (this.rest != null &amp;&amp; toCompare.rest != null) {
          return this.rest.equals(toCompare.rest);
        } else {
          return Boolean.TRUE;
        }
      } else {
        return Boolean.FALSE;
      }
    }

